SIMPLE: suit
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Suit
<hw>Suit</hw> <pr>(s⟦umac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>suite</ets>, F. <ets>suite</ets>, OF. <ets>suite</ets>,
<ets>sieute</ets>, fr. <ets>suivre</ets> to follow, OF.
<ets>sivre</ets>; perhaps influenced by L. <ets>secta</ets>. See
<er>Sue</er> to follow, and cf. <er>Sect</er>, <er>Suite</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of following or pursuing, as game;
pursuit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of suing; the process by which one endeavors
to gain an end or an object; an attempt to attain a certain result;
pursuit; endeavor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thenceforth the <qex>suit</qex> of earthly conquest shone.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The act of wooing in love; the solicitation of a
woman in marriage; courtship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rebate your loves, each rival <qex>suit</qex> suspend,⟦br⟧
Till this funereal web my labors end.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The attempt to gain an end by legal
process; an action or process for the recovery of a right or claim;
legal application to a court for justice; prosecution of right before
any tribunal; <as>as, a civil <ex>suit</ex>; a criminal <ex>suit</ex>; a
<ex>suit</ex> in chancery.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I arrest thee at the <qex>suit</qex> of Count Orsino.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In England the several <qex>suits</qex>, or remedial instruments
of justice, are distinguished into three kinds -- actions personal,
real, and mixed.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>That which follows as a retinue; a company of
attendants or followers; the assembly of persons who attend upon a
prince, magistrate, or other person of distinction; -- often written
<asp>suite</asp>, and pronounced <pr>sw⟦emac⟧t</pr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Things that follow in a series or succession; the
individual objects, collectively considered, which constitute a series,
as of rooms, buildings, compositions, etc.; -- often written
<asp>suite</asp>, and pronounced <pr>sw⟦emac⟧t</pr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A number of things used together, and generally
necessary to be united in order to answer their purpose; a number of
things ordinarily classed or used together; a set; <as>as, a
<ex>suit</ex> of curtains; a <ex>suit</ex> of armor; a <ex>suit</ex> of
clothes; a three-piece business <ex>suit</ex>.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Two
rogues in buckram <xex>suits</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Playing Cards)</fld> <def>One of the four sets of
cards which constitute a pack; -- each set consisting of thirteen cards
bearing a particular emblem, as hearts, spades, clubs, or diamonds;
also, the members of each such suit held by a player in certain games,
such as bridge; <as>as, hearts were her long
<ex>suit</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To deal and shuffle, to divide and sort⟦br⟧
Her mingled <qex>suits</qex> and sequences.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Regular order; succession.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every five and thirty years the same kind and <qex>suit</qex> of
weather comes again.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <specif>Hence: (derived from def 7)</specif>
<def>Someone who dresses in a business suit, as contrasted with more
informal attire;</def> <specif>specifically,</specif> <def>a person,
such as business executive, or government official, who is apt to view a
situation formalistically, bureaucratically, or according to formal
procedural criteria; -- used derogatively for one who is inflexible,
esp. when a more humanistic or imaginative approach would be
appropriate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Out of suits</b></col>, <cd>having no
correspondence.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Suit
and service</b></col> <fld>(Feudal Law)</fld>, <cd>the duty of
feudatories to attend the courts of their lords or superiors in time of
peace, and in war to follow them and do military service; -- called also
<altname>suit service</altname>.</cd> <au>Blackstone.</au> --
<col><b>Suit broker</b></col>, <cd>one who made a trade of obtaining the
suits of petitioners at court.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <col><b>Suit
court</b></col> <fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd>the court in which tenants
owe attendance to their lord.</cd> -- <col><b>Suit covenant</b></col>
<fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd>a covenant to sue at a certain court.</cd>
-- <col><b>Suit custom</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a service which
is owed from time immemorial.</cd> -- <col><b>Suit service</b></col>.
<fld>(Feudal Law)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Suit and service</cref>,
above.</cd> -- <col><b>To bring suit</b></col>. <fld>(Law)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To bring <xex>secta</xex>, followers or witnesses, to
prove the plaintiff's demand.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>In modern usage, to institute an action.</cd> -- <col><b>To follow
suit</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Follow</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos></cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To mimic the
action of another person; to perform an action similar to what has
preceded; <as>as, when she walked in, John left the room and his wife
<ex>followed suit</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col>long suit</col> <sd>(a)</sd>
<fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <cd>the suit{8} of which a player has the
largest number of cards in his hand; <as>as, his <ex>long suit</ex> was
clubs, but his partner insisted on making hearts trumps.</as>.</cd>
<specif>Hence:</specif> <mark>[fig.]</mark> <cd>that quality or
capability which is a person's best asset; <as>as, we could see from the
mess in his room that neatness was not his <ex>long suit</ex></as>.</cd>
-- <col>strong suit</col> <cd>same as <cref>long suit</cref>,
<sd>(b)</sd>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I think our <qex>strong suit</qex> is that we
can score from both the perimeter and the post.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Bill Disbrow
(basketball coach) 1998.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Rigid ideological consistency has
never been a <qex>strong suit</qex> of the Whole Earth Catalogue.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Bruce Sterling (The Hacker Crackdown, 1994)</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Suit
<hw>Suit</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Suited</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Suiting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fit; to adapt; to
make proper or suitable; <as>as, to <ex>suit</ex> the action to the
word</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be fitted to; to accord with; to become; to
befit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ill <qex>suits</qex> his cloth the praise of railing well.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Raise her notes to that sublime degree⟦br⟧
Which <qex>suits</qex> song of piety and thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To dress; to clothe.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So went he <qex>suited</qex> to his watery tomb.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To please; to make content; <as>as, he is well
<ex>suited</ex> with his place; to <ex>suit</ex> one's
taste</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Suit
<hw>Suit</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To agree; to accord; to be fitted;
to correspond; -- usually followed by <xex>with</xex> or
<xex>to</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The place itself was <qex>suiting</qex> to his care.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give me not an office⟦br⟧
That <qex>suits</qex> with me so ill.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To agree; accord; comport; tally; correspond;
match; answer.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suitability</ent>⟦br⟧
